{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75504eeb-5efa-4d2d-ad73-9a5235b3db0a","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You can find them in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for user-launched apps\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for system-wide crashes\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for lldb):\n\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps before running your app\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore dumps go to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log is usually sufficient — it contains the full native backtrace, register state, and loaded images. If it's a .NET runtime crash, you can symbolicate the runtime frames using the `Symbolicate-Crash.ps1` approach (invoke the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill if you need help with that).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84864976-d415-4915-a3d7-3bbcef1cacf7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":332,"requestId":"AC0E:420A3:14FB8F5:17605EA:6A067128"},"id":"941bddfb-159c-4380-ba2c-dcc9b3d68a67","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:50.470Z","parentId":"deb55ac4-6d05-41a0-b286-f57238a19f3a"}
